Here is the elegantly coded C++ implementation for sampleNextToken using Top-P sampling.

✨ Elegant Implementation: Top-P (Nucleus) Sampling
Top-P sampling works by selecting tokens only from the smallest possible set whose cumulative probability exceeds a threshold P (the nucleus). This allows the vocabulary size to dynamically adjust based on the probability distribution: a sharp distribution uses a small set, while a flat distribution uses a large set.

The implementation requires four steps:

Apply softmax to convert logits to probabilities.

Sort the tokens by probability.

Iterate through the sorted tokens, accumulating probability until the Top-P threshold is crossed.

Randomly sample one token from this "nucleus."

We'll introduce a default Top-P value of 0.9 and assume the class has a helper function for randomness (e.g., getRandomFloat(0.0f, 1.0f)).

